Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and finely chop @onion{1}(peeled and finely chopped). Remove and
discard any large stems from @kale{4%ounce}; chop into bite-size pieces if
necessary. Peel and thinly slice @garlic{2%clove}(peeled and thinly sliced).
Quarter @lemon{1}.

Once water is boiling, add @cavatappi pasta{6%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}.

Reserve 3/4 cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large pan over medium-high heat.
Add @shrimp{10%ounce} and onion; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook,
breaking up meat into pieces, until sausage is mostly cooked through and
onion is softened, ~{3-5%minutes}.

> Rinse shrimp under cold water, then pat dry with paper towels or open package
> of chicken and drain off any excess liquid. Swap in shrimp or chicken for
> sausage (no need to break up into pieces!).

Stir in kale and garlic; cook until sausage is cooked through and kale is
wilted, ~{3-5%minutes}. TIP: Add kale in batches if necessary.

Reduce heat to medium. Stir in @cream sauce base{4%ounce}, @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon},
@chicken stock concentrate{1}, 1/4 cup reserved pasta cooking water, and a big
squeeze of lemon juice. Cook, stirring occasionally, until thickened,
~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Reduce heat to low. Stir in drained cavatappi, half the @Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon}
(save the rest for serving), @butter{2%tablespoon}, and a squeeze of lemon juice.

> TIP: If needed, stir in more reserved cooking water a splash at a time until
> pasta is coated in a creamy sauce.

Divide pasta between bowls; top with remaining Parmesan. Serve with remaining
lemon wedges on the side.

> Shellfish is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.